<TITLE> Nine rivers overflow to worsen flood </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 27 (bdnews24.com)  Nine rivers were flowing above the danger levels at 14 points amid warnings of the floods taking a turn for the worse. The rivers Khowai at Habiganj, the Dharla at Kurigram and the Kapotaksho at Jhikargachha rose further. The rivers in the Brahmaputra and the Ganges basins might rise further in the next 24 hours, a Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre (FFWC) bulletin said Friday. The road connecting the Nalitabari bridge on Sirajganj-Kazipur road was washed away Friday morning. bdnews24.com correspondent Mahbub Alam Rony said fisheries and agriculture adviser CS Karim visited the spot at 11am and instructed authorities to quickly repair the damage. The army and police joined hands in the repair there. Sirajganj deputy commissioner Ibrahim Khalil said the waters breached the Brahmaputra flood control embankment Thursday at Palashpur under Kazipur upazila, washing away the approach road of Nalitabari bridge. The FFWC said all the rivers except one in the Brahmaputra and the Ganges basins registered further spate. The Teesta was flowing 25 cm above the danger mark at Dalia point in Rangpur. The Dharla river was flowing 3 cm above the danger level at Kurigram. The Jamuna was flowing 60 and 17 cm above the danger marks at Sirajganj and Aricha points. The Padma was flowing 46 cm and 23 cm above the danger levels at Goalanda and Bhagyakul points. The Surma was flowing 105 cm, 15 cm and 83 cm above the danger marks at Kanaighat, Sylhet and Sunamganj points. The Someshawari was flowing 148 cm above the danger mark Friday morning, though the flow has receded a little. The Gomti was flowing 49 cm above the danger mark at Debidwar point. The Khowai was flowing 90 cm above the danger mark at Habiganj point. The met office said most places of Dhaka, Chittagong, Rajshahi and Sylhet divisions and places of Barisal and Khulna divisions might see light to medium rainfall with squally to gusty winds. Influenced by the monsoon, places of Rajshahi, Dhaka, Chittagong, Sylhet and Barisal divisions might also have heavy to torrential rainfall. The day temperature might remain unchanged across the country. The maximum temperature in Dhaka Wednesday was recorded at 28 degrees Celsius and the minimum 24 degrees Celsius. The highest temperature countrywide Wednesday was recorded at 32 degrees Celsius at Jessore and the lowest 23.3 degrees Celsius at Rangamati. bdnews
